body:
I was writing a test macro to confirm that a type didn't implement a trait. For an invocation `assert_not_impl!(Type: Trait)`, it emits code like:

```rust
const _: () = {
    trait Blanket {}
    impl<T: Trait> Blanket for T {}
    impl Blanket for Type {}
};
```

The goal was to cause a trait impl conflict if the `Trait` was spuriously implemented. I found that while this worked for sized types, it didn't catch the error for unsized types. In other words, the following code fails to compile:

```rust
struct Foo;

trait Bar {}

impl Bar for Foo {}

const _: () = {
    trait Blanket {}
    impl<T: Bar> Blanket for T {}
    impl Blanket for Foo {}
};
```

...with this error:

```text
error[[E0119]](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/error-index.html#E0119): conflicting implementations of trait `_::Blanket` for type `Foo`
  --> src/lib.rs:10:5
   |
9  |     impl<T: Bar> Blanket for T {}
   |     -------------------------- first implementation here
10 |     impl Blanket for Foo {}
   |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ conflicting implementation for `Foo`
```

However, if we modify `Foo` to be an unsized type, the code compiles successfully:

```rust
struct Foo([u8]);

trait Bar {}

impl Bar for Foo {}

const _: () = {
    trait Blanket {}
    impl<T: Bar> Blanket for T {}
    impl Blanket for Foo {}
};
```

I'm not convinced that this is a bug, but it's certainly surprising, and might point to a bug.

## Version
1.65.0
